node.title: Question about solution of the equation
node.bodyText: There are 3 equations(a,b,c) in kernel. Can I write the discretization of another equation(d) in userobject and solve these four equations together? Are there any examples I can look at?

Hello
The number of equations is dictated by the number of variables.
You may form 3 equations with kernels, and write another one with a user object.
There are numerous examples of user objects contributing to the residual in:
the tensor mechanics module
https://github.com/idaholab/moose/tree/next/modules/tensor_mechanics/src/userobjects/lagrangian
the thermal hydraulics module
https://github.com/idaholab/moose/blob/next/modules/thermal_hydraulics/src/userobjects/ADBoundaryFlux3EqnFreeOutflow.C
the navier stokes module
https://github.com/idaholab/moose/blob/next/modules/navier_stokes/src/userobjects/INSFVRhieChowInterpolator.C
the ray tracing module as well (ray kernels) though there s a lot of inheritance going on, from a UO to a ray-kernel.
Guillaume

node.title: Edit Hostname within WSL
node.bodyText:
Hello MOOSE users,
I am trying to install MOOSE on the WINDOSW 10 and I am not very familiar with GitHub and computer environment configuration terms.
As a part of installation  on the "Edit Hostname within WSL" it askes to modify the host file. I run the "Notepad "C:\Windows\System32\Drivers\etc\hosts" at it opens a text file. My question is what should I do next?

should I , in the "#       127.0.0.1       localhost"  line  just replace the 127.0.01 with the result of hostname?
or , should I just add this line "127.0.0.1       <---- ADD THAT " at the end of the text file?

Thanks you for the help

You want to always append to this file, and not replace other lines already there. You'll want to figure out what your hostname is. That is achieved by running hostname in your cmd.exe terminal window:
Microsoft Windows [Version 10.0.19044.1586]
(c) Microsoft Corporation. All rights reserved.

C:\Users\Jason>hostname
DESKTOP-IA0VD92
For me, I would take DESKTOP-IA0VD92 and append the following line to my hosts file (located at: C:\Windows\System32\Drivers\etc\hosts):
127.0.0.1   DESKTOP-IA0VD92

node.title: Interface materials for DG kernels
node.bodyText:
Hello there,
I have created a DGkernel named VMNSDGKernel and want to apply it to the whole domain along with TotalLagrangianStressDivergence Kernel. The VMNSDGKernel needs to get some properties from a previously made interface material.  Is it possible to do so? I can't find any example that a DG kernel gets material properties from an interface material or any DGMaterial that inherit from InterfaceMaterial or Material.
In other words, for every element in the domain, Is it possible that the DG kernel get the face properties of element and neighbor from an interface material, without the need to breaking the mesh by blocks and without having interface boundary? If no, what are the alternatives?
When I tried to use my DG kernel with my previous interface material, I get the following error:
*** ERROR ***
The following error occurred in the object "tracaver_neighbor", of type "ComputeTractionAverJumpBubble".
MaterialBase::subdomainSetup in Material'tracaver_neighbor' needs to be implemented
Thanks a lot,
Amir

InterfaceMaterials are really only meant for use with InterfaceKernels. A regular Material should in most cases work fine with use of the getMaterialProperty and getNeighborMaterialProperty APIs. However, we do have an open issue for creation of an InternalSideMaterial at #14215 which is meant to solve the issues raised in #4335

node.title: Predicting/Knowing Through thickness location of shell element integration points.
node.bodyText:
I'm attempting to do some work with shell elements in MOOSE, and as part of this I need to extract curvature from the shell elements. To do this, I have been attempting to use the strain on the upper and lower integration points, however this is not giving me the correct result. I believe I have tracked down the issue to a detail mentioned in a comment on an example file:
# The stress_yy for the four elements at z = -0.57735 * (t/2) (first qp below mid-surface of shell) are:
# 3031.089 Pa, 2165.064 Pa, 1299.038 Pa and 433.0127 Pa. 

In file Beam_Bending_Moment_AD.i
This comment, and the way the stress is extracted by the auxkernel, indicates that in the second order case, the lower integration point is not located at -1/2 thickness, but instead -0.57735*1/2thickness. My question(s):

why is this the location of the integration point?
Where will the integration point be located in different through thickness orders with different numbers of integration points? For example, with fourth order through thickness there is one point below the midplane, one at the midplane and one above the midplane, but where are the above and below ones located?
If these values aren't known/communicated to users then it is impossible to know what the stress outputs given by the elements mean. If you take stress values at 0.57735*0.5 of your thickness without realising instead of the top of the shell, they will be artificially lowered.
@GiudGiud @neuphris any thoughts on this?

For the first question, this is determined by the quadrature rule used.
I m not very familiar with this, maybe @recuero will know who to hit up for this
@neuphris

Like @GiudGiud  mentioned, these integration points come from the Gauss quadrature points. For the second order, the quadrature points are +0.57735 and -0.57735. If you assume the thickness to be 't' with bottom as '0', you can transform the first qp (xi) from the parent domain [-1, 1] to  physical domain [a,b] or [0, t]  as:
x = a/2* (1- xi) + b/2 * (1 - xi) =  0 + t/2 (1-0.57735) = t/2 - t/2 * 0.57735 .
Similarly you can find the location of the quadrature points on the physical domain with higher order.

Okay, that makes some sense. Between these points is variation linear or does the interpolation between them change depending on the order (I'm guessing the second). Basically I'm trying to use MOOSE for some shell element FEA and I need shell top and bottom stresses, not stresses at gauss points, so I need a way to extrapolate from the output points to surface stresses (where the stress is maximum in bending and the typical FE output point for a shell). Sorry for pestering, it would be helpful if this information (which is essential to using shells for any serious work) was more easily accessible somewhere.
I have not compared the stresses at the surfaces, but I believe you can take the value of the stress at the Gauss QP and map it to the node using the shape function.

The inheritance relationship changed from inheriting  Kernel.C  to inheriting ArrayKernel.C. The data type of the variables also changed from "const VariableValue & _u;" to "const ArrayVariableValue & _u;". There are severe questions about data types that I would like to ask.


How do I express the component of _u in the code, which brackets should I use, [] or ()?


I need to use the value of _u in another file, so assign the value of _u in the kernel file to another file by means of a pointer. My current compilation succeeds in writing the assignment  in the kernel file


for (size_t i=0; i<_count; ++i)
  _cfd_data._u[i] = _u[i];

Declare the new variable in another file
RealEigenVector _u[10];
I don't know if this makes sense, is there any connection between the data types RealEigenVector and ArrayVariableValue?


I found the data type RealEigenMatrix in MooseType.h. If I replace the Real type in the code when I have a single variable with the RealEigenVector type which is suitable for multiple variables, should I replace RealVectorValue with RealEigenMatrix, and how should a variable of type RealEigenMatrix represent its components?


For the previous RealTensorValue type, I did not find a matching type suitable for multiple variables. Is there any data type that can represent a variable with more than 2 dimensions? For example, I want to represent a variable with a dimension of 5 x 5 x 3 x 3, which can be seen as a large matrix nested within a small matrix, where each component of the large 5 x 5 matrix is a small 3 x 3 matrix, what data type is suitable for such a variable?


I also found the data types RealVectorArrayValue and RealTensorArrayValue in MooseType.h. They both seem to have a limit on the number of columns, with a dynamic number of rows and a Moose::dim number of columns. Can the number of columns for these two data types exceed 3?


Can any variable in the code directly represent the order of _u of a multivariate? Which self-contained function in moose can be used to get the norm directly for variables of type RealEigenVector?

Hello
Please read the array variable documentation, I feel it will answer a lot of your questions.
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/source/variables/ArrayMooseVariable.html
For question 4, array is a 1D array and is your only option for a multi-component variable with an arbitrary number (here 225) of components IF that is the non linear variable.
If that object is NOT the non linear variable, then you may look at using a RankFourTensor instead

we define the .norm() class member attribute routine for a lot of classes. I cant recall if RealEigenVector is one of them.

Guillaume

node.title: Which kernel should I use if I want to treat time derivative term as 0 in CH equation?
node.bodyText:

Which kernel should I use if I don't want to consider time derivative term in CH equation?
I want to set time derivative term as 0.
Currently, I am using Coupledtimederivative, kernel to deal with the time derivative term, can I simply delete this part?
